{
  "card_id": "support_level",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Support Level",
  "aliases": [
    "support",
    "Support",
    "support area",
    "Support Zone",
    "support zone"
  ],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "A price zone or level where buying pressure repeatedly emerges, preventing further declines and often causing upward reversals. Typically identified by at least two prior bounces from approximately the same price area. Strong support shows abrupt momentum moves into and away from the level, indicating high reliability for future bounces.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a horizontal price zone where price has reversed upward on at least two prior occasions, forming a floor.",
    "Upon retest, confirm a bullish reaction with sharp bullish candles or bullish candlestick patterns (e.g., hammer).",
    "Assess momentum: strong support features abrupt moves into and away from the level, with large real bodies, indicating reliability.",
    "Recognize that if the support level is broken, it may later flip to act as resistance upon a retest.",
    "Optionally, combine with indicator signals like RSI crossing outside lower Bollinger Band for additional confirmation of extreme momentum."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Support levels provide areas to consider buying with expectation of a bounce. A confirmed bullish reaction (candlestick patterns, momentum) upon retest increases confidence for long entries, with stop-loss placed just below. A break below indicates potential further downside, with the level potentially becoming future resistance. Conversely, if support fails, it may offer short opportunities on a retest as resistance. Use of indicators like RSI can complement confirmation.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Assuming support will always hold without recognizing weakening signs (e.g., smaller bounces, hesitation, increased volatility, bearish reversal signals).",
    "Entering solely based on historical support levels without waiting for real-time bullish confirmation (e.g., momentum candles, candlestick patterns).",
    "Treating support as an exact price line rather than a zone or area.",
    "Placing stop-loss orders exactly at the support level without leaving wiggle room, risking premature stop-outs from minor price wicks.",
    "Ignoring the quality of the bounce; weak or grinding reactions suggest vulnerability to a breakdown.",
    "Failing to anticipate that a broken support level can flip and act as resistance on a retest."
  ],
